Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

  • This soccer database comes from Kaggle and is well suited for data analysis and machine learning. It contains data for soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016. For this part. I will use two datasets, the Player and Player_Attributes. for more information click here

Question(s) for Analysis¶

The following question are going to be answered throughout the analysis¶

  1. What is the distribution of the overall rating on the given dataset?
  2. Which varible is best characteristics of the higly rated player?
  3. Which type of prefered foot (left or right) is associated with high player rating?
  4. Do player with higher dribble skill receive better ratings?
  5. What is the name of the player that has better rating?
  6. Which players had the most penalties?

  • As we see the above figures, the histogram shows a skewed distribution graph.   • lastly, we can use the mean or median to perform further analysis towards the dependent variable since, the distribution is not symmetric.

# Next checking correlation using scatterplots
def scatter_plot(df):
    count=1
    plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 20))
    for c in df:
        plt.subplot(6,1,count)
        sb.scatterplot(x= df_pa[c], y = df_pa["overall_rating"])
        count+=1
    plt.show();

scatter_plot(df_pa1) # calling the function for the selected variables

The other way of measuring correlation¶

  • Calculating the mean value of dependent and independent variable and plotting bar chart is also possible to determine the correlation between them.

Accordingly, as we can see from the figures, the variable potential has higher positive correlation with the dependent variable i.e. overall_rating. They have better relationship between them and we can say that as the potential increases the overall rating of the player would also go up. Next to that the variable vision has better correlation with the dependent variable out of the rest.
  • It has been also visualized and explored using bar chart taking the mean value of the variables. The finding out of the later technique is also analogous to the former one.

Research Question 3 : Which type of prefered foot (left or right) is associated with high player rating?¶

  • To answer this quetion, groupby is introduced to group in terms of left and right preferred foot player. After that, an average value of overall rating for each group has to be computed. Based on that, visualzation would be conducted.
In [24]:
# 1. let's define a function for handling repetative functionalities and for this question
def myPlot(df, grpVar, yVar, color = ('purple', 'blue')):
    # df: is the data frame pass from the callee
    # grpVar: is the variable that represent the graph on the x axis
    # yvar: the varible that shows its value on the y axis
    
    # 2. plot, using the groupby with the mean value, it plots on the x axis which is important feature of groupby 
    df.groupby(grpVar)[yVar].mean().plot.bar(edgecolor ='black', figsize =[15,8], rot = 0, width = 0.8, color = color);
    grpVar = grpVar.replace("_", " ") # replacing the _ with space
    yVar = yVar.replace("_ ", " ")  # replacing the _ with space
    # 3. Add title and format
    plt.title(f'Average {yVar} by {grpVar}'.title(), fontsize = 14, weight = 'bold')
    # 4. Adding x lable
    plt.xlabel(grpVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    # 5 Add y label
    plt.ylabel(f'Average {yVar}'.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
In [25]:
# clling the plot function 
myPlot(df_pa, 'preferred_foot', 'overall_rating')

Report on Question #3:¶

As we can see from the figuer, players who are preferred with either left or right foot are rated close similarly with slight differences. All in all, we can say that, the left foot player has higher overall rating based on the above finding.

Question 4: Do player with higher dribble skill receive better ratings?¶

  • in this question, it is expected to identify the median of the variable dribbling and creating two sub dataframe. Next, the avearge of overall_rating of each class will be computed.
In [26]:
# create dribbling ability variable 
# 1 let the default is high
df_pa['dribbling ability'] = 'high'
# 2. change the rows below median to low
df_pa.loc[df_pa['dribbling'] < df_pa['dribbling'].median(), 'dribbling ability'] = 'low'
# call the plot fumction
myPlot(df_pa, 'dribbling ability', 'overall_rating', color = ('purple', 'yellow'))

Report on Question #4:¶

  • as we can see from the above visulization, players with high dribbiling skill has better overall rating. To do this the low dribbler and high dribbler player observation has been classified using the median. Then again these two class are computed towards the average value of the overall rating and generated the above figuer. Thus, players with high dribbling skill has better overall rating value.

Conclusions¶

  • in this soccer dataset analysis, basically six questions have been tried to addressed. Before addressing the questions, some paramount activities such as understanding the datasets which may helpful to draw questions has made. In addition, it has been gone through data wrangling, cleaning and assessing of the datasets.

  • Coming to the question and finding, it has been tried to identify the dependent and independent variable and the distribution of the independent variable over the given dataset has been visualized and described. Questions related to correlation between dependent variable and some selected independent variable has been visualized using different technique and outcomes been recorded. Other question related the identifying name of highly rated plyer and player that had the most penality, identifying the impact of dribbler players and preferred foot players on the overall rating of the given player attribute datasets has been tried to be addressed with all possible techniques and mechanisms.

  • Coming to the limitation.

    • Some variables are filled with unfamiliar value which makes it difficult for cleaning and analyzing, particularly the attacking_work_rate and defensive_work_rate of the player attribute.
    • In this analysis, issues related to outliers are not considered.
    • During the analysis, sample observations are selected though there could be variables that may have different outcomes apart from this work.
    • Some regression analysis methods such as linear and logistic regression are helpful to understand better, eventually it is difficult to include in this analysis due to the data limitation, such as categorical and unknown values are present in some of the observation on the given dataset.
    • There is no statistical inference performed to test the significance of the findings.

  • Note that, for each question, findings are presented under the report section on that specific question number.
